2. Show a graphical overview of the data

The figure shows the relationship among different variables. Totally there are 166 subjects including 110 females and 56 males. 7 variables include age, attitude, deep combined with deep questions, stra with strategiic questions, surf with surface questions, points. Most subjects are at the age of 20-30. The points of attitude and deep questions for male subjects are higher than that of female. But the points of strategic and surface quenstions for female subjects are higher than that of males. However there is little difference of the overall points between genders. The variable of points has a relatively close relationship with attitude, with correlation value 0.437.

create a regression model with three explanatory variables targeted points

model1 <- lm(points ~ attitude + stra + surf, data = learning2014)

The target variable point is fitted to three explanatory variables: attitude, stra and surf. According to the results of the model, surf does not have a statistically significant relationship with the target variable. So, surf is removed from the fitting model and points is modelled according to attitude and stra again.

remove variable surf and remodel

model2 <- lm(points ~ attitude + stra, data = learning2014)

4. Interpret fitted model

summary(model2)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = points ~ attitude + stra, data = learning2014)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -17.6436  -3.3113   0.5575   3.7928  10.9295 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)   8.9729     2.3959   3.745  0.00025 ***
## attitude      3.4658     0.5652   6.132 6.31e-09 ***
## stra          0.9137     0.5345   1.709  0.08927 .  
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 5.289 on 163 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.2048, Adjusted R-squared:  0.1951 
## F-statistic: 20.99 on 2 and 163 DF,  p-value: 7.734e-09

In Model2, ‘points’ is the target and both ‘attitude’and ’stra’ are the explanatory variables. The formula is \(points=8.9729+3.4658*attitude+0.9137*stra\). We could expect an average points of 8.9729 for all gender subjects with no any points in attitude and strategis question. If stra remains constant, points will differ by 3.4658 unit on average when attitude differed by 1 unit.Similarly, points will change 0.9137 unit when sta differed by one unit if attitude keeps constant. The regression modle account for 20.48% of the variance. Since the points can be affected by other factors apart from attitude and sta, so the multiple R-squared value is lower than 50%. However, we have statistically a significant predictor in attitude, we can still use the formula for prediction.

5. Diagnostic plots

par(mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(model2, which=c(1,2,5))

The Residuals vs Fitted values plot examines if the errors have constant variance. The graph shows a reasonable constant variance without any pattern. The Normal QQ-polt checks if the errors are normally distributed. We see from the graph a very good linear model fit, indicating a normally distributed error set. The Residuals vs Leverage confirms if there are any outliers with high leverage. From the graph, it shows that all the leverage are below 0.06, indicating good model fitting.

loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)

The Boston data is about housing value in suburbs of Boston. 14 Variables used to assess housing value are as following:

crim per capita crime rate by town.
zn proportion of residential land zoned for lots over 25,000 sq.ft.
indus proportion of non-retail business acres per town.
chas Charles River dummy variable (= 1 if tract bounds river; 0 otherwise).
nox nitrogen oxides concentration (parts per 10 million).
rm average number of rooms per dwelling.
age proportion of owner-occupied units built prior to 1940.
dis weighted mean of distances to five Boston employment centres.
rad index of accessibility to radial highways.
tax full-value property-tax rate per $10,000.
ptratio pupil-teacher ratio by town.
black 1000(Bk ??? 0.63)2 where Bk is the proportion of blacks by town.
lstat lower status of the population (percent).
medv median value of owner-occupied homes in $1000s

  • the function for lda biplot arrows
lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

5. interpretations of PCA on the standardized human data

  1. Maternal mortality ratio is positively related to adolescent birth rate.
  2. Expected years of schooling and life expectancy at birth have a positive correction withthe ratio of Female and Male populations with secondary education in each country.
  3. All varibles except Parli.F and Labo.FM have same direction with PC1 axis. the directons of Parli.F and Labo.FM are the same with PC2
